## 🤖 SLIDE 3: Machine Learning Model — Steel Area Prediction

### What to Present

The ML component uses a **Random Forest Regressor** (scikit-learn) trained on **5,000 synthetic beam design samples**.

### Training Pipeline

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A["data/generate_data.py\nGenerate 5000 samples"] --> B["beam_dataset.csv\n(span, load, fck, fy → steel_area)"]
    B --> C["model/train_model.py\nTrain Random Forest"]
    C --> D["model.pkl\n(45 MB serialized model)"]
    D --> E["api/main.py\nLoad & predict at runtime"]
```

### How the Training Data is Generated

From `data/generate_data.py`:
```python
span = random.uniform(3, 10)     # 3m to 10m
load = random.uniform(10, 50)    # 10 to 50 kN/m
fck  = random.choice([20, 25, 30])  # concrete grades
fy   = 460                       # steel grade (constant)
```

Each sample runs through the **rule-based** `design_beam()` function to get the "correct" steel area → this becomes the training label.

### The Model

From `model/train_model.py`:
```python
model = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=100)
model.fit(X, y)  # X = [span, load, fck, fy], y = steel_area
```

- **Algorithm:** Random Forest Regressor (ensemble of 100 decision trees)
- **Features (inputs):** `span`, `load`, `fck`, `fy`
- **Target (output):** `steel_area` (mm²)
- **Serialization:** Saved with `joblib` as `model.pkl` (~45 MB)

### How Prediction Works at Runtime

From `api/main.py` (line 193–200):
```python
input_df = pd.DataFrame([{
    "span": span,
    "load": max(w, 1),    # Total factored UDL
    "fck": fck,
    "fy": fy
}])
steel_area = model.predict(input_df)[0]
```

### Speaker Notes

> *"Why use ML if we already have rule-based calculations? The ML model serves as a rapid estimator and cross-validator. It was trained on data generated by our own rule engine, so it learns the relationship between structural parameters and required reinforcement. In production, both the ML prediction and the rule-based calculation run — giving us a dual-check system. The Random Forest was chosen because it handles non-linear relationships well, is robust to outliers, and doesn't require feature scaling."*

### Questions You Might Get (and Answers)

| Question | Answer |
|---|---|
| Why Random Forest? | Handles non-linear relationships, no feature scaling needed, interpretable |
| Why synthetic data? | Real beam design data is scarce; our rule engine generates ground-truth labels |
| How accurate is it? | Trained on rule-engine output, so it mirrors BS 8110 calculations closely |
| Why 100 trees? | Standard default; provides good bias-variance tradeoff without overfitting |
| Model size is 45MB — why? | 100 decision trees with 5000 samples creates many nodes; acceptable for server deployment |

